Package com.rapidminer.belt.buffer

Class Buffers

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.rapidminer.belt.buffer.Buffers
  • public final class Buffers
extends java.lang.Object
    Utility methods for creating mutable temporary buffers. These buffers can then be used to create immutable Columns.
    Author:
    Gisa Meier, Michael Knopf

      • realBuffer

        public static NumericBuffer realBuffer​(int length)
        Creates a buffer of the given length to create a Column of type Column.TypeId.REAL. The buffer is initially filled with Double.NaN. If the buffer is completely overwritten anyway realBuffer(int, boolean) can be used with initialize false instead.
        Parameters:
        length - the length of the buffer
        Returns:
        the new buffer
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the given size is negative

      • categoricalBuffer

        public static <T> CategoricalBuffer<T> categoricalBuffer​(int length)
        Creates a buffer of the given length to create a Column of category Column.Category.CATEGORICAL. The buffer supports the maximum number of categories supported by Belt (2147483647). The buffer is initially filled with CategoricalReader.MISSING_CATEGORY.

        Please note, that is recommended to use categoricalBuffer(int, int) instead whenever the number of categories is known in advance.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the element type
        Parameters:
        length - the length of the buffer
        Returns:
        the new buffer
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the given size is negative

      • categoricalBuffer

        public static <T> CategoricalBuffer<T> categoricalBuffer​(int length,
                                                         int categories)
        Creates a buffer of the given length to create a Column of category Column.Category.CATEGORICAL with at most the given number of categories. Trying to use the buffer with more than the specified number of categories might result in an error. The buffer is initially filled with CategoricalReader.MISSING_CATEGORY.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the element type
        Parameters:
        length - the size of the buffer
        categories - the number of categories
        Returns:
        the new buffer
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the given size or number of categories is negative

      • categoricalBuffer

        public static <T> CategoricalBuffer<T> categoricalBuffer​(Column column,
                                                         java.lang.Class<T> type)
        Creates a buffer to create a Column of category Column.Category.CATEGORICAL by copying the data from the given column. The buffer supports the maximum number of categories supported by Belt (2147483647). The buffer is initially filled with CategoricalReader.MISSING_CATEGORY.

        Please note, that is recommended to use categoricalBuffer(Column, Class, int) instead whenever the number of categories is known in advance.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the element type
        Parameters:
        column - the column to derive the buffer from
        type - the element type
        Returns:
        the new buffer
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if any of the arguments is null
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the column is not categorical or if the specified type is incompatible with the given column

      • categoricalBuffer

        public static <T> CategoricalBuffer<T> categoricalBuffer​(Column column,
                                                         java.lang.Class<T> type,
                                                         int categories)
        Creates a buffer to create a Column of category Column.Category.CATEGORICAL with at most the given number of categories by copying the data from the given column. Trying to use the buffer with more than the specified number of categories might result in an error. The buffer is initially filled with CategoricalReader.MISSING_CATEGORY.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the element type
        Parameters:
        column - the column to derive the buffer from
        type - the element type
        categories - the number of categories
        Returns:
        the new buffer
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if any of the arguments is null
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the column is not categorical, if the specified type is incompatible with the given column, or if the given number of categories is negative
